      <h1 class="Overskrift1">Sakura Festival</h1>
      <p class="Tekst1">
        The Committee of the Copenhagen Sakura Festival was established in
        February, 2008 to arrange the cultural event Copenhagen Sakura Festival
        with the help of the Japanese Embassy in Denmark, the Municipality of
        Copenhagen and other Japan-related cultural and private organizations.
      </p>

      <div class="Billede">
        <img src="Billeder/image7.webp" alt="Sakura Festival" />
      </div>

      <div class="redboks">
        <div class="Billede2"><img src="Billeder/image8.webp" alt="Mad" /></div>

        <h1 class="Overskrift2">Sakura Festivals Motivation</h1>

        <p class="Tekst2">
          In Japan people love and admire Sakura blossom and almost everybody go
          out to enjoy its beauty together with families, friends, lovers,
          office-mates and so forth wherever and whenever Sakura bloom. Once a
          year Sakura connects people and people meet people under Sakura trees.
          It is also the utmost and fundamental goal of the Committee.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h1 class="Overskrift3">How It Started</h1>
      <p class="Tekst3">
        The original idea came from the noble deed of donation of 200 cherry
        blossom (Sakura) trees by Mr. Seiichi Takaki, President of Andersen
        Institute of Bread & Life, the holding company of Andersen Group of
        Hiroshima City, and the employees of the company. The donated Sakura
        trees were planted in Langelinie Park. Mr. Takaki who is Honorary Consul
        of Denmark was appointed to the honorable position of ambassador of H.C.
        Andersen on the occasion of the 200th anniversary of H.C. Andersenâ€™s
        birthday in 2005.
      </p>

